				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} v.w=\left| \frac{\Sigma _{i=1}^n \log _2 T_i}{n}-\frac{\Sigma _{j=1}^m \log _2 N_j}{m}\right| \end{aligned}$$\end{document}v.w=Σi=1nlog2Tin-Σj=1mlog2Njmwhere \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$T_i$$\end{document}Ti is the expression value of tumour sample i, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$N_j$$\end{document}Nj is the expression value of a normal sample j, and n and m are the numbers of tumour and normal samples, respectively. Intuitively, a high FC value corresponds to a high possibility of a cancer gene. Thus, it is reasonable to use the FC values as the weights of genes.

